| Notes                   = * There are no after-credits scenes in the theatrical release.
* A short film called {{ml|Deadpool: No Good Deed}} was shown before the theatrical runs of this film.
* A black-and-white version of the film, titled ''Logan: Noir,'' had a one-night theatrical run in the United States on May 16, 2017.{{cite|ref=true|url=https://twitter.com/mang0ld/status/858058912288841728|title=Suggestion. Hard core B&W loving LOGAN fans should not make any plans on the evening of May 16th.|work=Twitter|first=James|last=Mangold|date=29 April 2017|accessdate=13 May 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170501053856/https://twitter.com/mang0ld/status/858058912288841728|archivedate=1 May 2017}} This version is also featured on the home video release of the film.
* According to interviews with Logan star Hugh Jackman and director James Mangold, the film is intended to take place in the [[Earth-17315|possible future]] after ''[[X-Men: Days of Future Past (film)|Days of Future Past]]''.{{cite|ref=true|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/movies/a819480/hugh-jackman-says-logan-different-universe-x-men-films/|title=Logan is not set in the same universe as the X-Men movies, says Hugh Jackman|work=Digital Spy|first=Rosie|last=Fletcher|date=January 21, 2017|accessdate=October 12, 2024|archiveurl=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/nXnFQ|archivedate=October 12, 2024}}{{cite|ref=true|url=https://comicbook.com/marvel/news/logan-director-james-mangold-x-men-sequels-franchise-future/|title=Logan Director On The X-Men Franchise’s Open Future ][“I gave them many escape valves. We take place in 2029, and X-Men [Days of Future Past] ends in 2024,” Mangold said. “There’s five blank years there that are wide open to seeing how things got from here to there. Or else you could do what I would advocate, which is imagine a different world and create a new movie, and you don’t need the permission of the other movies.|work=ComicBook.com|first=Joseph|last=Schmidt|date=September 5, 2017|archiveurl=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/9xgie|archivedate=November 17, 2024}}{{cite|ref=true|url=http://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/logan-11-revelations-director-james-mangold/|title=Logan: 11 Revelations From Director James Mangold|work=Empire|first=John|last=Nugent|date=March 7, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170909065225/http://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/logan-11-revelations-director-james-mangold/|archivedate=September 8, 2017}}{{cite|ref=true|url=https://twitter.com/mang0ld/status/871482277045207040|title=James Mangold on Twitter: "Not a dystopian possibility. Simply a possibility."|work=twitter|first=James|last=Mangold|date=January 21, 2017|archiveurl=https://vignette.wikia.nocookie.net/marveldatabase/images/5/5e/20240819%EF%BC%BF171728.png/revision/latest?cb=20240825140314&format=original|archivedate=August 25, 2024}}{{cite|ref=true|url=https://twitter.com/mang0ld/status/823196909707751425|title=James Mangold on Twitter: "Because we take place after all the other movies, we have freedom. That's all he meant. Breathe,"|work=twitter|first=James|last=Mangold|date=January 23, 2017|accessdate=October 21, 2024|archiveurl=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/ttoXf|archivedate=October 21, 2024}}
* The film's screenplay, written by Scott Frank, James Mangold, and Michael Green, was nominated for the {{WP|Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay}} at the {{WP|90th Academy Awards}}. It is the first time a film based off Marvel Comics was nominated at the Academy Awards for screenwriting.
| Trivia                  = 
[[File:Victor Creed (Earth-17315) from Logan (film) deleted scene 001.jpg|thumb|Sabretooth toy in a deleted scene]]
<!--* The page of the ''X-Men'' comic book Logan shows Professor X was penciled by [[Joe Quesada]] and inked and colored by [[Dan Panosian]].{{cite|ref=true|url=http://joequesada.tumblr.com/post/156273923373/logan-since-this-page-is-already-public-as-seen|title=Joe Quesada - LOGAN  Since this page is already public, as seen...|work=Tumblr|first=Joe|last=Quesada|date=23 January 2017|accessdate=24 January 2017}}-->
* Director [[James Mangold]] had an idea for a cameo for [[Sabretooth]], to whom Logan would've gone for help when on the run in the gambling town. The idea wasn't developed beyond that, and it eventually didn't make it to the final script.{{cite|ref=true|url=http://www.cinemablend.com/news/1631149/what-logan-was-planning-to-do-with-sabretooth|title=What Logan Was Planning To Do With Sabretooth|work=CinemaBlend|first=Eric|last=Eisenberg|date=3 March 2017|accessdate=4 March 2017}} A Sabretooth toy (Toy Biz [[Marvel Legends]] Series V) appears in one of the deleted scenes.
* Among the genetic donors for the X-23 children is [[Christopher Bradley (Earth-17315)|Christopher Bradley]], who [[Christopher Bradley (Earth-10005)|previously appeared]] in ''[[X-Men Origins: Wolverine (film)|X-Men Origins: Wolverine]]'' and was portrayed by {{WP|Dominic Monaghan}}.
* The film was originally intended to open on the Westchester incident, and would clearly establish which of the X-Men were killed. However, this was dropped early in the process, particularly as it would potentially change the focus of the film.{{cite|ref=true|url=http://comicbook.com/marvel/2017/05/22/logan-westchester-incident-xmen-dead/|title=Logan Nearly Opened With The Death Of The X-Men|work=comicbook.com|First=Jay|Last=Jayson|date=22 May 2017}}
* James Mangold has confirmed that the depiction of Logan's death in this film was an intentional callback to [[Yukio (Earth-10005)|Yukio's]] premonition of his death in ''[[The Wolverine (film)|The Wolverine]].''{{cite|ref=true|url=http://www.denofgeek.com/uk/movies/logan/47848/logan-how-its-ending-was-teased-in-the-wolverine|title=Logan: how its ending was teased in The Wolverine|work=Den of Geek|First=Simon|Last=Brew|date=March 10, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606050554/https://www.denofgeek.com/uk/movies/logan/47848/logan-how-its-ending-was-teased-in-the-wolverine|archivedate=June 6, 2017}}{{cite|ref=true|url=https://twitter.com/mang0ld/status/839883693392977920|title=James Mangold on Twitter: "Well done, Maurice."|work=twitter|first=James|last=Mangold|date=March 10, 2017|accessdate=October 20, 2024|archiveurl=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/YQ5Yw|archivedate=October 20, 2024}}
* One of the deleted scenes connects ''Logan'' with ''[[X-Men: The Last Stand]]:''  At the dinner table, Kathryn Munson asked if Logan was married. Xavier claims that Logan was married to Jean Grey, and that Logan also killed her.<ref>https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/logan-deleted-scene-jean-grey-was-depressing-1006240</ref>
* Logan makes a reference to "Fantasyland," a location found at Disneyland Park in Anaheim, CA.

